      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Oliver Phelps (1749-1809) was Deputy Commissary of the Continental Army during the American Revolution.  
		Following the war he was appointed a judge, was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives, and became a 
		land speculator in western New York state.  </p>
		
		<p>Nathaniel Gorham (1738-1796) was a politician and 
		merchant from Massachusetts. He served as delegate from Massachusetts to the Continental Congress and was 
		one of the signers of the United States Constitution on September 17, 1787.</p>
		
		<p>In 1788, a syndicate formed by Phelps and Gorham bought preemptive rights to six million acres of land 
		in what is now western New York State from the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, and the pre-emptive right 
		to the title on the land from the Six Nations of the Iroquois Confederacy.  The transaction is known as the Phelps and Gorham Purchase.  Unable to make subsequent payments 
		on the land, they were eventually forced to sell much of it to Senator Robert Morris of Philadelphia.</p>
		
		</bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Phelps and Gorham Purchase Collection</emph> consists of correspondence, deeds,  and account books.</p><p>The six account books, five with covers and one without, are apparently early manuscript copies dating from approximately 1830, of accounts dating from between 1789 and 1807.  Several of the volumes contain two sets of information, reversed from one another (that is, one must flip the volume over so that the back cover becomes the front).</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
